      "type": "Term",
      "front": "The Immigrant Quest for Freedom",
      "back": "For two decades, Debs crisscrossed the country preaching that control of the economy by a democratic government held out the hope of uniting \"political equality and economic freedom.\" As a champion of the downtrodden, Debs managed to bridge the cultural divide between New York's Jewish immigrants, prairie socialists of the West, and native-born intellectuals attracted to the socialist ideal. TABLE 18.1 Rise of the City, 1880–1920 Like their nineteenth-century predecessors, the new immigrants arrived imagining the United States as a land of freedom, where all persons enjoyed equality before the law, could worship as they pleased, enjoyed economic opportunity, and had been emancipated from the oppressive social hierarchies of their homelands. \"Effective freedom,\" wrote the philosopher John Dewey, was a positive, not a negative, concept—the \"power to do specific things.\" As such, it depended on \"the distribution of powers that exists at a given time.\" Thus, freedom inevitably became a political question.",
